ral concerns and intellectual commitments of the Greco-Roman Mediterranean world. Purity, Body, and Self in Early Rabbinic Literature adds a new dimension to the study of practices of self-making in antiquity by suggesting that not only philosophical exercises but also legal paradigms functioned as sites through which the self was shaped and improved.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPurity, RitualxJudaism. 0aRabbinical literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aRabbinical literature. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh  aancient judaism.  aantiquity.  abible.  abiblical language.  abiblical law.  abiblical practices.  abodily self.  aconsciousness.  acultural studies.  aearly rabbis.  agreco roman mediterranean world.  ahistory of judaism.  ahuman environment.  ajewish studies.  ajudaism.  amishnah.  anonhuman environment.  apalestinian legal codex.  aphilosophy of halakah.  arabbinic texts.  areligion.  areligious studies.  areligious.  aritual impurity.  aritual purity.  as mark taper foundation imprint in jewish studies series.  aself making.  aself reflection.  aspiritual.  asubjectivity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028063240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095821040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958210423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520958210/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY